tyle=3D"margin:10px 0">Nic Carter was a prominent Bitcoin advocate, GP at C=
astle Island Ventures, and co-founder of Coin Metrics. He's long been a Bit=
coin maximalist voice =E2=80=94 bullish on BTC, often critical of altcoins =
(including Solana</p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Since late 2025, he's gone =
extremely hard on quantum computing as the biggest long-term risk to Bitcoi=
n (and ECC-based chains generally). He wrote a multi-part Substack series (=
"Bitcoin and the Quantum Problem"), did podcasts (e.g., Bankless: "Bitcoin =
Has 3 Years to Survive the Quantum Threat"), and repeatedly argued elliptic=
 curve cryptography (ECDSA/Schnorr on secp256k1, used by Bitcoin) is vulner=
able to Shor's algorithm on a sufficiently powerful quantum computer. </p><=
h3>But the real story is Project Eleven - HIS INVESTMENT</h3><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:10px 0">Castle Island Ventures (Nic's firm) led a $20M Series A into P=
roject Eleven (P11) in January 2026 at a $120M valuation. Nic has been very=
 public about it and is closely involved (board/advisory level per disclosu=
res). Project Eleven is explicitly a post-quantum cryptography infrastructu=
re company for digital assets - aka the more Quantum FUD he spreads the bet=
ter his bags do. </p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">So yes =E2=80=94 Nic isn't =
just opining. His firm has a direct financial stake in the quantum-risk nar=
rative gaining traction across crypto. Heightened fear/urgency helps his ba=
gs.  </p><h3>The Solana/Anza situation</h3><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">nic_c=
arter never spoke with anyone at Anza. Someone with actual engineering skin=
 in the game is calling out Nic's claims as uninformed.  it's refreshing to=
 see technical pushback. </p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">h.t Sanjay for head=
